---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const pharmaBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Pharma &amp; Medical Device Sales Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Pharma &amp; medical device sales mortgage from a lender who reads W-2 base + commission, quota accelerator structure, President&rsquo;s Club bonus, RSU stock compensation, quarterly spiff income, and sign-on/retention bonuses as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working pharmaceutical and medical device sales representatives carry one of the most W-2-dominant qualifying profiles in any sales profession &mdash; with substantial RSU stock compensation, President&rsquo;s Club bonuses, and quota-driven accelerator commission structures that generalist underwriting routinely misclassifies. <strong>Per BLS OEWS May 2024 data, sales representatives wholesale &amp; manufacturing technical &amp; scientific products run a median wage of $99,710 with top 10% over $213,460. These numbers substantially understate top-performing pharma and device reps: established pharmaceutical sales representatives at Pfizer (NYSE: PFE), Merck (NYSE: MRK), Johnson &amp; Johnson (NYSE: JNJ), Bristol Myers Squibb (NYSE: BMY), AbbVie (NYSE: ABBV), Eli Lilly (NYSE: LLY), AstraZeneca (NASDAQ: AZN), Novartis (NYSE: NVS), Roche, GlaxoSmithKline, and Sanofi commonly earn $150K&ndash;$300K OTE through W-2 base plus commission plus quarterly bonuses plus RSU stock vesting; medical device sales reps at Medtronic (NYSE: MDT), Stryker (NYSE: SYK), Boston Scientific (NYSE: BSX), Zimmer Biomet (NYSE: ZBH), Smith+Nephew, Abbott (NYSE: ABT), Edwards Lifesciences (NYSE: EW), Intuitive Surgical (NASDAQ: ISRG), and Becton Dickinson (NYSE: BDX) commonly $200K&ndash;$500K OTE through higher variable comp structures with case-by-case OR operating-room based commission; top performers consistently making President&rsquo;s Club at either category $400K&ndash;$800K+ through accelerator commission past quota plus elevated RSU grants plus retention bonuses; and the elite tier in specialty oncology, surgical implants, robotic surgery (Intuitive Surgical da Vinci, Stryker Mako), and rare disease specialty pharma $600K&ndash;$1.5M+ through high-value product complexity</strong>. The qualifying mechanic that matters: aggregating W-2 base + commission + quarterly bonus + President&rsquo;s Club + RSU vesting + retention bonuses under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average, plus B3-3.1-09 stock vesting analysis for RSU compensation, produces the actual income picture working reps carry &mdash; not the base-salary-only number that generalist underwriters sometimes substitute.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how pharma/device sales qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in W-2 base + commission, quota accelerator structure, President&rsquo;s Club bonus, RSU stock compensation aggregation, quarterly spiff income, and sign-on/retention bonuses for pharma and medical device sales mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/8376280/pexels-photo-8376280.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Medical device sales representative meeting with hospital purchasing team" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Pharma+Sales';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$150K-$800K+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Established working pharma rep ($150K-$300K typical) and medical device rep ($200K-$500K typical) OTE range; top performers consistently making President&rsquo;s Club $400K-$800K+; elite specialty $600K-$1.5M+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">W-2 dominant</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Pharma and medical device sales is overwhelmingly W-2 employer-paid commission income, in contrast to realtors, MLOs, and insurance agents who often operate as 1099 Schedule C self-employed</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">RSU vesting</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Substantial RSU stock compensation at publicly-traded pharma and device companies, typically $30K-$200K+ annually vesting for established reps after multi-year retention through long-term incentive plans</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">President&rsquo;s Club</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Top 10-15% of reps consistently making President&rsquo;s Club tier qualify for trip, cash bonus, elevated RSU grant, and accelerator commission past quota &mdash; the elite income tier marker</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3938022/pexels-photo-3938022.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Pharmaceutical sales representative" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Pharma';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working pharmaceutical and medical device sales representatives on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>W-2 base salary plus quarterly commission tied to quota attainment plus accelerator commission past 100% quota plus annual President&rsquo;s Club bonus for top performers (typically 10-15% of reps qualify) plus quarterly spiff income from short-term promotional sales contests plus RSU stock compensation vesting on multi-year schedules from long-term incentive plans (LTIP) at publicly-traded employers including Pfizer, Merck, Johnson &amp; Johnson, Bristol Myers Squibb, AbbVie, Eli Lilly, AstraZeneca, Novartis, Roche, GlaxoSmithKline, Sanofi, Medtronic, Stryker, Boston Scientific, Zimmer Biomet, Smith+Nephew, Abbott, Edwards Lifesciences, Intuitive Surgical, and Becton Dickinson plus sign-on bonuses for newly recruited reps plus retention bonuses for proven performers in competitive territories plus auto allowance and vehicle/fuel programs (typically $9K-$15K annually) plus district/regional sales manager override income for reps promoted to management plus strategic account manager bonuses for reps managing key hospital, IDN (Integrated Delivery Network), or GPO (Group Purchasing Organization) relationships, all under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average plus B3-3.1-09 for RSU vesting analysis</strong>. A new pharma rep in years 1-2 building territory, an established pharma rep with primary care or specialty product responsibility, an established medical device rep with case-by-case OR-based commission, a top-performing President&rsquo;s Club consistent rep with elevated RSU grants, and a district/regional sales manager combining personal management override with team performance bonus each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. <strong>This is the first sales sub-page where W-2 income is dominant rather than 1099 Schedule C &mdash; reflecting the employer-paid commission structure that distinguishes pharma and device sales from real estate, mortgage, insurance, and securities sales professions covered elsewhere in the Sales Professionals hub.</strong> Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other sales professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sales professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Pharma/device sales mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every pharma or medical device sales rep should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">W-2 dominant</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Pharma and medical device sales is overwhelmingly W-2 employer-paid commission income, qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> as variable income with 24-month average. This contrasts sharply with realtors, MLOs, and insurance agents who often operate as 1099 Schedule C self-employed. The W-2 dominance simplifies the qualifying mechanic but requires proper documentation of all variable components.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">RSU equity</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">RSU stock compensation from long-term incentive plans (LTIP) at publicly-traded employers is a substantial income component for established reps. RSU vesting income qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-09</a> with vesting schedule documentation. For tenured reps at major pharma or device companies, RSU vesting commonly adds $30K-$200K+ annually.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Quota accelerators</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Pharma and device sales commission structures use quota-based accelerator mechanics: commission rate increases past 100% of quota (typically to 150-200% of base commission rate) and may accelerate further past 110-120% quota. President&rsquo;s Club tier (typically top 10-15% of reps) receives accelerated commission plus annual trip, cash bonus, and elevated RSU grant.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Open Payments</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">CMS Open Payments transparency reporting under the Physician Payments Sunshine Act (Section 6002 of the Affordable Care Act) requires manufacturers to report payments to physicians and teaching hospitals. This regulatory framework doesn&rsquo;t affect mortgage qualifying directly but provides context for the pharma/device industry sales environment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your pharma/device sales career</div>
        <h2>Pharma &amp; medical device sales mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of a pharma or medical device sales career has its own qualifying logic. A new rep in years 1-2 building territory has a different mortgage path than an established pharma rep, an established medical device rep with case-based commission, a top performer consistently making President&rsquo;s Club, or a district/regional manager combining personal management override with team performance bonus.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New rep (Years 1&ndash;2)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Recently hired pharma or device rep at established manufacturer (Pfizer, Merck, J&amp;J, AbbVie, Lilly, Medtronic, Stryker, Boston Scientific) with W-2 base + ramping commission. Limited 24-month variable income history."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $90K&ndash;$140K W-2 base + ramping commission</li>
            <li>Sign-on bonus typically $10K-$30K plus relocation</li>
            <li>RSU vesting just beginning if any LTIP grants</li>
            <li>Conventional with W-2 documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-rep mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established pharma rep</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established pharmaceutical sales rep at Pfizer, Merck, J&amp;J Pharma, Bristol Myers Squibb, AbbVie, Lilly, AstraZeneca, Novartis, Roche, GSK, or Sanofi with consistent 2-year+ territory performance. Primary care or specialty product responsibility."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $150K&ndash;$300K W-2 base + commission + bonus</li>
            <li>2-year+ variable income history supports B3-3.1-01</li>
            <li>RSU vesting $25K-$80K annually from LTIP grants</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming or Jumbo</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established pharma mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established medical device rep</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established medical device sales rep at Medtronic, Stryker, Boston Scientific, Zimmer Biomet, Smith+Nephew, Abbott, Edwards Lifesciences, Intuitive Surgical, or Becton Dickinson. Case-by-case or OR-based commission structure with higher variable comp."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $200K&ndash;$500K W-2 base + commission + bonus</li>
            <li>Case-based or OR-based commission with higher variable %</li>
            <li>RSU vesting $40K-$150K annually from LTIP grants</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo typical</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See established device mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Top performer / President&rsquo;s Club consistent</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Top performer consistently making President&rsquo;s Club tier (top 10-15% of reps). Accelerator commission past quota, elevated RSU grants, additional retention bonuses, possibly transitioning to strategic account or training roles."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $400K&ndash;$800K+ across all components</li>
            <li>Accelerator commission past 100-120% quota</li>
            <li>Elevated RSU grants $100K-$300K+ annually from LTIP</li>
            <li>Multi-source W-2 + RSU + retention bonus aggregation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See top performer mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">District/Regional sales manager</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"District or regional sales manager promoted from individual contributor rep role. Combines personal management override on team production with team performance bonus, plus continuing RSU vesting from LTIP grants and elevated management-tier grants."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $250K&ndash;$600K W-2 base + override + bonus + RSU</li>
            <li>Team production override structure</li>
            <li>Elevated management-tier RSU grants</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with multi-component W-2 documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See manager mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your pharma or medical device sales mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every pharma and medical device rep file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your career stage, whether you specialize in pharma vs medical device sales, your RSU stock compensation tier, and whether you have transitioned to district or regional sales management.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; W-2 base + commission + quarterly bonus + President&rsquo;s Club (the rep default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for working pharma and medical device sales reps. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, W-2 base salary plus quarterly commission tied to quota attainment plus quarterly bonus plus annual President&rsquo;s Club bonus (for top performers) qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. Quota structures typically pay base commission at 100% quota with accelerator commission rates of 150-200% past 100% quota, sometimes additional acceleration past 110-120% quota. President&rsquo;s Club bonus (typically 10-15% of reps qualify) includes additional cash bonus, trip valued at $5K-$10K, and elevated RSU grant for the following year. All components aggregate into qualifying variable income.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; W-2 + RSU stock compensation aggregation (the high-tier method)</h3>
      <p>For established reps with substantial RSU stock compensation from long-term incentive plan (LTIP) grants. RSU compensation qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-09</a> as other source of income with vesting schedule documentation showing continuing vesting through at least 3 years post-application. RSU grant value depends on rep tier (typical individual contributor RSU grants $20K-$60K annually) plus elevated grants for President&rsquo;s Club qualifiers and management tier reps. RSU vesting income aggregates with base W-2 + commission + bonuses under combined B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.1-09 analysis. For tenured top performers at major pharma or device companies, RSU vesting commonly adds $80K-$200K+ to annual qualifying income.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Multi-year sign-on / retention bonus structures (the transition method)</h3>
      <p>For reps with active sign-on bonus structures from recent hiring or retention bonus programs for proven performers in competitive territories. Sign-on bonuses typically structured as $10K-$50K paid at hire plus additional payments at 12-month and 24-month anniversaries to support retention. Retention bonuses for established reps typically $25K-$100K+ paid as multi-year vesting incentive to retain key territory performance. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, multi-year bonus structures with documented vesting schedules and continuing employment requirements qualify as continuing variable income with proper employer documentation. The compensation letter from HR documenting the bonus schedule supports the qualifying analysis.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; District/regional sales manager (multi-component W-2)</h3>
      <p>For reps promoted to district or regional sales management roles combining personal compensation with team production override. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, manager W-2 income includes elevated base salary (typically $140K-$220K for district managers, $200K-$320K for regional managers), management override commission on team production (typically 5-15% of team aggregate commission), management performance bonus tied to team quota attainment, and elevated RSU grants from management-tier LTIP. The multi-component management W-2 commonly aggregates $250K-$600K+ with proper documentation of each component through HR compensation letter. <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/3401" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 3401</a> wage definitions apply to all W-2 components.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/3938022/pexels-photo-3938022.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a pharma or medical device sales file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working pharma and medical device sales rep files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the pharma/device W-2 multi-component pattern properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Quota-based accelerator commission structure</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Pharma and device sales commission structures use quota-based accelerator mechanics: base commission rate to 100% quota, then accelerator commission rate (typically 150-200% of base) past 100% quota, sometimes further acceleration past 110-120% quota. For a rep at 130% of quota, accelerator commission commonly produces 30-50% of total commission income. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, accelerator commission qualifies as continuing variable income with 2-year history. Generalist underwriters sometimes don&rsquo;t understand the accelerator mechanic and undercount commission income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">President&rsquo;s Club bonus (top 10-15% of reps)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">President&rsquo;s Club tier qualification (typically top 10-15% of reps based on quota attainment, growth, and product mix) brings annual cash bonus ($15K-$50K typical), recognition trip valued at $5K-$10K, and elevated RSU grant for the following fiscal year. President&rsquo;s Club consistent reps (multi-year qualifiers) carry the bonus as continuing variable income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a> with multi-year history documenting the bonus continuity. Generalist underwriters often classify as "discretionary not stable" without doing the documentation work.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">RSU stock compensation from LTIP grants</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">RSU stock compensation from long-term incentive plans (LTIP) at publicly-traded employers (Pfizer, Merck, J&amp;J, BMS, AbbVie, Lilly, AstraZeneca, Novartis, Roche, GSK, Sanofi, Medtronic, Stryker, Boston Scientific, Zimmer Biomet, Abbott, Edwards Lifesciences, Intuitive Surgical, BD) qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-09</a> as other source of income with vesting schedule documentation. For established reps, RSU vesting commonly $30K-$200K+ annually. For top performers and managers, RSU can exceed $200K. Generalist underwriters often refuse RSU vesting income or substantially discount it as "speculative future stock price."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Quarterly spiff and SPIF promotional bonuses</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Quarterly spiff (Sales Performance Incentive Funds) bonuses for short-term promotional sales contests are common in pharma and device sales, typically $1K-$5K per qualifying contest with multiple contests per quarter. For active reps consistently winning quarterly spiff contests, annual spiff income commonly $8K-$25K supplementing base commission. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, recurring spiff income qualifies as continuing variable income with 2-year history when documented through HR records and W-2 detail.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Auto allowance and vehicle/fuel programs</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Pharma and device reps typically receive auto allowance, company vehicle, or vehicle reimbursement program valued at $9K-$15K annually depending on employer. The auto component flows through W-2 as additional taxable income (vehicle allowance) or as non-taxable reimbursement (mileage). For mortgage qualifying purposes, the taxable auto allowance component aggregates into W-2 income; the non-taxable reimbursement provides cost offset for the rep&rsquo;s personal vehicle expense. Reduces effective cost of ownership for the rep&rsquo;s personal vehicle and improves debt-to-income calculation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Sign-on and retention bonus structures with vesting</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Sign-on bonuses for newly recruited reps (typically $10K-$50K paid in installments over 12-24 months with vesting) and retention bonuses for proven performers (typically $25K-$100K+ as multi-year vesting incentive) are common in pharma and device sales. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, multi-year bonus structures with documented vesting schedules and continuing employment requirements qualify as continuing variable income with proper HR compensation letter documenting the bonus schedule.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your pharma/device sales situation</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your pharma or medical device sales mortgage situation.</h2>
