          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My RSU grants vest over 4 years. Can I count vesting that comes after my mortgage close?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; future RSU vesting from existing grants qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-09</a> with vesting schedule documentation showing continuing vest through at least 3 years post-application. We document the existing grants with grant agreements and vesting schedules. RSU vesting income calculated from documented existing grants (not speculative future grants) qualifies as continuing income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a strategic account manager for major IDN customers. How does that comp structure work?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Strategic account manager (SAM) roles in medical device sales typically combine elevated base salary with strategic account performance bonuses tied to large IDN, GPO, or health system customer relationships. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the multi-component SAM W-2 qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. We document the SAM structure with HR compensation letter showing the account assignment and performance metrics.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also in pharma/device sales. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-rep households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year W-2 histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full B3-3.1-01 analysis on each W-2 plus B3-3.1-09 RSU vesting on each LTIP grant history. Combined household income from two established pharma/device reps commonly $400K-$1M+ supports $1M-$2M+ qualifying. Two-RSU households also benefit from combined vesting income aggregation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I got a substantial retention bonus to stay in my territory. How does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Retention bonus structures with multi-year vesting tied to continuing employment qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as continuing variable income during the active vesting period. We document the bonus schedule with HR letter showing remaining installments and continuing employment requirements. Generalist underwriters sometimes refuse retention bonus as "one-time non-continuing" &mdash; the vesting schedule documentation supports continuing treatment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I exercise my vested stock to use for down payment?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; vested stock can be sold and used for down payment through normal asset documentation. We document the source of funds as stock sale proceeds with brokerage statements showing the sale transaction. Tax implications (typically short-term or long-term capital gains depending on holding period from vest date) should be reviewed with your CPA. Stock sale proceeds for down payment are common and well-understood by underwriting.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company offers Employee Stock Purchase Plan (ESPP). Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">ESPP participation provides discount on company stock purchase through payroll deduction (typically 15% discount with 6-month or 12-month offering periods). ESPP shares acquired through the plan represent a source of additional stock holdings on the balance sheet but are not typically aggregated into qualifying income separately from base W-2. The post-tax ESPP contributions reduce take-home pay but build stock asset position over time.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse pharma/device sales files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Five reasons: (1) using W-2 base salary alone instead of total variable W-2 with proper B3-3.1-01 24-month average; (2) President&rsquo;s Club bonus classified as "discretionary not stable" without multi-year qualification documentation; (3) RSU vesting refused entirely as "speculative future stock" instead of properly aggregated under B3-3.1-09 with vesting schedule; (4) retention bonus treated as "one-time non-continuing" rather than multi-year vesting; (5) accelerator commission structure mis-modeled or undercounted. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads pharma/device W-2 multi-component structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My territory was reorganized through company restructuring. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Territory reorganizations are common in pharma and device sales. We document the new territory assignment through HR letter showing continuing employment, post-reorg quota and product responsibility, and any compensation structure changes. If the new territory has different commission characteristics, we provide pro-forma analysis. The continuing W-2 employment continuity supports qualifying through B3-3.1-01.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering transitioning from pharma to medical device sales. How should I time my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Channel transitions between pharma and device sales create new-employment underwriting where the prior pharma W-2 history supports continuing employment in the same broad profession but the device employer would need to be established. Strategic options: (1) close mortgage in current pharma role BEFORE the transition (uses established 2-year W-2 history); (2) wait 12-24 months post-device-transition to establish the new-employer 2-year history; (3) co-borrower file with spouse W-2 providing stability during transition. We model the options.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My medical device company is private (not publicly traded). Does that change RSU treatment?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Private company equity (RSU, stock options, profits interests) requires different documentation than public company RSU. Private equity grants typically have less liquid market value, more complex vesting and exercise structures, and limited liquidity events. For private company device reps, we coordinate documentation of the grant structure and any recent secondary or tender offer transactions providing valuation comparables. Pre-IPO device companies in late-stage growth (potential IPO candidates) may have substantial paper equity value.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for pharma/device reps?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No specialty pharma-or-device-specific products are widely available. What matters is finding a broker who understands W-2-dominant variable income with proper multi-component aggregation: B3-3.1-01 base + commission + accelerator + bonus + spiff, B3-3.1-09 RSU vesting analysis with continuing schedule, and multi-year qualification documentation for President&rsquo;s Club, retention, and sign-on bonus structures. Conventional Conforming and Jumbo done right produces strong outcomes.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My auto allowance is $11K. Does that count toward qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Auto allowance flows through W-2 as additional taxable income and aggregates into the total W-2 variable income for B3-3.1-01 24-month average treatment. Non-taxable mileage reimbursement (separate from auto allowance) doesn&rsquo;t flow through W-2 but reduces personal vehicle cost. We document the auto allowance through W-2 detail.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use Asset-Depletion to qualify on substantial stock holdings?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; for reps with significant post-vesting liquid stock holdings, Asset-Depletion Non-QM qualifies on liquid assets amortized over 360 months as implied income. Useful for tenured reps with $500K-$2M+ of liquid stock holdings (post-vest, freely tradeable shares) where the implied asset-depletion income exceeds W-2 income tier. Pricing carries 0.5-1% rate premium vs Conventional. We model Asset-Depletion alongside conventional B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.1-09 to identify optimal path.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 90-120 days before you intend to make an offer. Pharma and device sales files benefit from runway because of multi-component W-2 aggregation, RSU vesting analysis requiring grant documentation, President&rsquo;s Club bonus continuity documentation, retention or sign-on bonus vesting analysis, and possible coordination with HR for compensation letter documentation. For reps with substantial RSU vesting, additional runway helps document the vesting schedule through brokerage and HR records.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What HR compensation letter should I request from my employer for mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Request HR compensation letter covering: base salary, commission calculation methodology (quota structure with accelerator mechanics), 24-month commission history, President&rsquo;s Club qualification criteria and history, quarterly bonus/spiff structure, RSU grant history with vesting schedules, retention or sign-on bonus structure with remaining vesting, auto allowance details, and current employment status with continuing employment verification. The comprehensive HR letter supports proper B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.1-09 underwriting analysis.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

